All Implemented Interfaces:
Cursor
public class SelectionCursor
extends BaseCursor

this class produces a Cursor by iterating thru a SelectionSet's DataIDs. For each DataID found, the method getData() is called with that DataID as parameter, which is expected to return the Data associated with the DataID. Subclasses of this class can modify the behaviour of getData(), but the default behaviour is to obtain the Data by calling the getData() method of the SelectionSet's target Selectable Dataset.

Constructor Detail

SelectionCursor

public SelectionCursor(SelectionSet sset)
constructs the SelectionCursor for the given SelectionSet. This implementation first calls init(sset) then calls peek(). If you want to write a subclass, you'll want to over-ride this constructor, first call init(sset), perform any other initializations, then call peek() last

Parameters:
sset - the SelectionSet for which a Cursor is created

SelectionCursor

public SelectionCursor()
Normally, you won't use this constructor. It is provided to allow the strategy outlined in the other constructor. A null constructor is required for that procedure. This implementation does nothing

peek

protected void peek()
this implementation obtains the next DataID from the SelectionSet, then calls getData() using that DataID. peek() will repeatedly call getData() until it returns non-null result - this makes it possible for a FeatureClass to dynamically update its database and not suffer consequences if a DataID is no longer present

peek in class BaseCursor
